Text: '
Unusually among the Olympic deities, Apollo had two cult sites that had widespread influence: '
Begin Reference: Delos
End Reference: Delos
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: Delphi
End Reference: Delphi
Text: '. In cult practice, '
Begin Reference: Delos
k: null
Text: 'Delian Apollo'
End Reference: Delos
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: Pythian Apollo
End Reference: Pythian Apollo
Text: ' (the Apollo of Delphi) were so distinct that they might both have shrines in the same locality.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Burkert 1985:143.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Apollo's '
Begin Reference: Cult (religion)
k: null
Text: 'cult'
End Reference: Cult (religion)
Text: ' was already fully established when written sources commenced, about 650 BCE. Apollo became extremely important to the Greek world as an oracular deity in the '
Begin Reference: Archaic Greece
k: null
Text: 'archaic period'
End Reference: Archaic Greece
Text: ', and the frequency of '
Begin Reference: theophoric names
End Reference: theophoric names
Text: ' such as '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Apollodorus'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' or '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Apollonios'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' and cities named '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Apollonia'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' testify to his popularity. Oracular sanctuaries to Apollo were established in other sites. In the 2nd and 3rd century CE, those at '
Begin Reference: Didyma
End Reference: Didyma
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: Clarus
End Reference: Clarus
Text: ' pronounced the so-called "theological oracles", in which Apollo confirms that all deities are aspects or servants of an '
Begin Reference: Monism#Monism, pantheism, and panentheism
k: null
Text: 'all-encompassing, highest deity'
End Reference: Monism#Monism, pantheism, and panentheism
Text: '. "In the 3rd century, Apollo fell silent. '
Begin Reference: Julian the Apostate
End Reference: Julian the Apostate
Text: ' (359 - 61) tried to revive the Delphic oracle, but failed."'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'DDD']
