Section [0] Mythology
Paragraph
Section [1] Birth
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Apollo Artemis Brygos Louvre G151.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '250px'
k: null
Text: 'Apollo (left) and '
Begin Reference: Artemis
End Reference: Artemis
Text: '. '
Begin Reference: Brygos
End Reference: Brygos
Text: ' (potter signed), tondo of an Attic red-figure cup c. 470 BC, '
Begin Reference: Musée du Louvre
End Reference: Musée du Louvre
Text: '.'
End Reference: File:Apollo Artemis Brygos Louvre G151.jpg
Text: '
When Zeus' wife '
Begin Reference: Hera
End Reference: Hera
Text: ' discovered that Leto was pregnant and that Zeus was the father, she banned '
Begin Reference: Leto
End Reference: Leto
Text: ' from giving birth on "terra firma". In her wanderings, Leto found the newly created floating island of '
Begin Reference: Delos
End Reference: Delos
Text: ', which was neither mainland nor a real island. She gave birth there and was accepted by the people, offering them her promise that her son would be always favourable toward the city. Afterwards, Zeus secured Delos to the bottom of the ocean. This island later became sacred to Apollo.'
Paragraph
Text: 'It is also stated that Hera kidnapped '
Begin Reference: Eileithyia
End Reference: Eileithyia
Text: ', the goddess of childbirth, to prevent Leto from going into labor. The other gods tricked Hera into letting her go by offering her a necklace, nine yards (8 m) long, of amber. Mythographers agree that '
Begin Reference: Artemis
End Reference: Artemis
Text: ' was born first and then assisted with the birth of Apollo, or that Artemis was born one day before Apollo, on the island of '
Begin Reference: Ortygia
End Reference: Ortygia
Text: ' and that she helped Leto cross the sea to Delos the next day to give birth to Apollo. Apollo was born on the seventh day ('
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'ἑβδομαγενής'
End Template: lang
Text: ', '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'hebdomagenes'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ')'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Begin Template: LSJ
k: null
Text: 'e(bdomagenh/s'
k: null
Text: 'ἑβδομαγενής'
k: null
Text: 'shortref'
End Template: LSJ
Text: '.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' of the month Thargelion —according to Delian tradition—or of the month Bysios—according to Delphian tradition. The seventh and twentieth, the days of the new and full moon, were ever afterwards held sacred to him.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Youth
Text: '
Four days after his birth, Apollo killed the '
Begin Reference: chthonic
End Reference: chthonic
Text: ' dragon '
Begin Reference: Python (mythology)
k: null
Text: 'Python'
End Reference: Python (mythology)
Text: ', which lived in '
Begin Reference: Delphi
End Reference: Delphi
Text: ' beside the '
Begin Reference: Castalian Spring
End Reference: Castalian Spring
Text: '. This was the spring which emitted vapors that caused the oracle at Delphi to give her prophecies. Hera sent the serpent to hunt Leto to her death across the world. To protect his mother, Apollo begged '
Begin Reference: Hephaestus
End Reference: Hephaestus
Text: ' for a bow and arrows. After receiving them, Apollo cornered Python in the sacred cave at Delphi.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Children of the Gods'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' by Kenneth McLeish, page 32.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Apollo killed Python but had to be punished for it, since Python was a child of '
Begin Reference: Gaia (mythology)
k: null
Text: 'Gaia'
End Reference: Gaia (mythology)
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Hera then sent the giant '
Begin Reference: Tityos
End Reference: Tityos
Text: ' to kill Leto. This time Apollo was aided by his sister Artemis in protecting their mother. During the battle Zeus finally relented his aid and hurled Tityos down to '
Begin Reference: Tartarus
End Reference: Tartarus
Text: '. There he was pegged to the rock floor, covering an area of '
Begin Template: convert
k: null
Text: '9'
k: null
Text: 'acre'
k: null
Text: 'm2'
End Template: convert
Text: ', where a pair of '
Begin Reference: vulture
End Reference: vulture
Text: 's feasted daily on his liver.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Trojan War
Text: '
Apollo shot arrows infected with the plague into the Greek encampment during the '
Begin Reference: Trojan War
End Reference: Trojan War
Text: ' in retribution for '
Begin Reference: Agamemnon
End Reference: Agamemnon
Text: ''s insult to '
Begin Reference: Chryses
End Reference: Chryses
Text: ', a priest of Apollo whose daughter '
Begin Reference: Chryseis
End Reference: Chryseis
Text: ' had been captured. He demanded her return, and the Achaeans complied, indirectly causing the anger of Achilles, which is the theme of the '
ItalicBold: 2
Begin Reference: Iliad
End Reference: Iliad
ItalicBold: 2
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Text: 'In the '
ItalicBold: 2
Begin Reference: Iliad
End Reference: Iliad
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', when '
Begin Reference: Diomedes
End Reference: Diomedes
Text: ' injured '
Begin Reference: Aeneas
End Reference: Aeneas
Text: ', Apollo rescued him. First, '
Begin Reference: Aphrodite
End Reference: Aphrodite
Text: ' tried to rescue Aeneas but Diomedes injured her as well. Aeneas was then enveloped in a cloud by Apollo, who took him to Pergamos, a sacred spot in '
Begin Reference: Troy
End Reference: Troy
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Apollo aided '
Begin Reference: Paris (mythology)
k: null
Text: 'Paris'
End Reference: Paris (mythology)
Text: ' in the killing of '
Begin Reference: Achilles
End Reference: Achilles
Text: ' by guiding the arrow of his bow into '
Begin Reference: Achilles
End Reference: Achilles
Text: '' heel. One interpretation of his motive is that it was in revenge for Achilles' sacrilege in murdering '
Begin Reference: Troilus
End Reference: Troilus
Text: ', the god's own son by '
Begin Reference: Hecuba
End Reference: Hecuba
Text: ', on the very altar of the god's own temple.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Admetus
Text: '
When Zeus struck down Apollo's son Asclepius with a lightning bolt for resurrecting '
Begin Reference: Hippolytus (mythology)
k: null
Text: 'Hippolytus'
End Reference: Hippolytus (mythology)
Text: ' from the dead (transgressing '
Begin Reference: Themis
End Reference: Themis
Text: ' by stealing '
Begin Reference: Hades
End Reference: Hades
Text: ''s subjects), Apollo in revenge killed the '
Begin Reference: Cyclops
k: null
Text: 'Cyclopes'
End Reference: Cyclops
Text: ', who had fashioned the bolt for Zeus.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Pseudo-Apollodorus, '
ItalicBold: 2
Begin Reference: Bibliothke
End Reference: Bibliothke
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' iii. 10.4.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Apollo would have been banished to '
Begin Reference: Tartarus
End Reference: Tartarus
Text: ' forever for this, but was instead sentenced to one year of '
Begin Reference: Penal labour
k: null
Text: 'hard labor'
End Reference: Penal labour
Text: ', due to the intercession of his mother, '
Begin Reference: Leto
End Reference: Leto
Text: '. During this time he served as shepherd for '
Begin Reference: Admetus
k: null
Text: 'King Admetus'
End Reference: Admetus
Text: ' of '
Begin Reference: Pherae
End Reference: Pherae
Text: ' in '
Begin Reference: Thessaly
End Reference: Thessaly
Text: '. Admetus treated Apollo well, and, in return, the god conferred great benefits on Admetus.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Apollo helped Admetus win '
Begin Reference: Alcestis
End Reference: Alcestis
Text: ', the daughter of '
Begin Reference: Pelias
k: null
Text: 'King Pelias'
End Reference: Pelias
Text: ' and later convinced the '
Begin Reference: Moirai
k: null
Text: 'Fates'
End Reference: Moirai
Text: ' to let Admetus live past his time, if another took his place. But when it came time for Admetus to die, his parents, whom he had assumed would gladly die for him, refused to cooperate. Instead, Alcestis took his place, but '
Begin Reference: Heracles
End Reference: Heracles
Text: ' managed to "'
ItalicBold: 2
Begin Reference: Coercion
k: null
Text: 'persuade'
End Reference: Coercion
ItalicBold: 2
Text: '" '
Begin Reference: Thanatos
End Reference: Thanatos
Text: ', the god of death, to return her to the world of the living.'
Paragraph
