Begin Reference: Amphion
End Reference: Amphion
Text: ', boasted of her superiority to Leto because she had fourteen children ('
Begin Reference: Niobids
End Reference: Niobids
Text: '), seven male and seven female, while Leto had only two. Apollo killed her sons, and Artemis her daughters. Apollo and Artemis used poisoned arrows to kill them, though according to some versions of the myth, a number of the Niobids were spared ('
Begin Reference: Chloris
End Reference: Chloris
Text: ', usually). Amphion, at the sight of his dead sons, either killed himself or was killed by Apollo after swearing revenge.'
Paragraph
Text: 'A devastated Niobe fled to '
Begin Reference: Spil Mount
k: null
Text: 'Mount Sipylos'
End Reference: Spil Mount
Text: ' in '
Begin Reference: Asia Minor
End Reference: Asia Minor
Text: ' and turned into stone as she wept. Her tears formed the river '
Begin Reference: Achelous
End Reference: Achelous
Text: '. Zeus had turned all the people of Thebes to stone and so no one buried the Niobids until the ninth day after their death, when the gods themselves entombed them.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Consorts and children
Text: '
Love affairs ascribed to Apollo are a late development in Greek mythology.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: '"The love-stories themselves were not told until later." '
Begin Reference: Karl Kerenyi
End Reference: Karl Kerenyi
Text: ', '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'The Gods of the Greeks'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' 1951:140.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Their vivid anecdotal qualities have made some of them favorites of painters since the Renaissance, the result being that they stand out more prominently in the modern imagination.'
