Begin Reference: Leucothea
End Reference: Leucothea
Text: ' was daughter of '
Begin Reference: Orchamus
End Reference: Orchamus
Text: ' and sister of '
Begin Reference: Clytia
End Reference: Clytia
Text: '. She fell in love with Apollo who disguised himself as Leucothea's mother to gain entrance to her chambers. Clytia, jealous of her sister because she wanted Apollo for herself, told Orchamus the truth, betraying her sister's trust and confidence in her. Enraged, Orchamus ordered Leucothea to be buried alive. Apollo refused to forgive Clytia for betraying his beloved, and a grieving Clytia wilted and slowly died. Apollo changed her into an incense plant, either heliotrope or sunflower, which follows the sun every day.'
Paragraph
Begin Reference: Marpessa
End Reference: Marpessa
Text: ' was kidnapped by '
Begin Reference: Idas
End Reference: Idas
Text: ' but was loved by Apollo as well. '
Begin Reference: Zeus
End Reference: Zeus
Text: ' made her choose between them, and she chose Idas on the grounds that Apollo, being immortal, would tire of her when she grew old.'
Paragraph
Begin Reference: Castalia
End Reference: Castalia
Text: ' was a '
Begin Reference: nymph
End Reference: nymph
Text: ' whom Apollo loved. She fled from him and dove into the '
Begin Reference: castalian Spring
k: null
Text: 'spring'
End Reference: castalian Spring
Text: ' at Delphi, at the base of '
Begin Reference: Mt. Parnassos
End Reference: Mt. Parnassos
Text: ', which was then named after her. Water from this spring was sacred; it was used to clean the Delphian temples and inspire the priestesses. In the last '
Begin Reference: oracle
End Reference: oracle
Text: ' is mentioned that the "water which could speak", has been lost for ever.'
Paragraph
Text: 'By '
Begin Reference: Cyrene (mythology)
k: null
Text: 'Cyrene'
End Reference: Cyrene (mythology)
Text: ', Apollo had a son named '
Begin Reference: Aristaeus
End Reference: Aristaeus
Text: ', who became the patron god of cattle, '
Begin Reference: fruit trees
End Reference: fruit trees
Text: ', hunting, husbandry and '
Begin Reference: bee-keeping
End Reference: bee-keeping
Text: '. He was also a '
Begin Reference: culture-hero
End Reference: culture-hero
Text: ' and taught humanity dairy skills, the use of nets and traps in hunting, and how to cultivate olives.'
Paragraph
Begin Reference: Hecuba
End Reference: Hecuba
Text: ', was the wife of King '
Begin Reference: Priam
End Reference: Priam
Text: ' of '
Begin Reference: Troy
End Reference: Troy
Text: ', and Apollo had a son with her named '
Begin Reference: Troilus
End Reference: Troilus
Text: '. An '
Begin Reference: oracle
End Reference: oracle
Text: ' prophesied that Troy would not be defeated as long as Troilus reached the age of twenty alive. He was ambushed and killed by '
Begin Reference: Achilleus
End Reference: Achilleus
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Begin Reference: Cassandra
End Reference: Cassandra
Text: ', was daughter of Hecuba and Priam, and Troilus' half-sister. Apollo fell in love with Cassandra and promised her the gift of prophecy to seduce her, but she rejected him afterwards. Enraged, Apollo indeed gave her the ability to know the future, with a curse that she could only see the future tragedies and that no one would ever believe her.'
Paragraph
Begin Reference: Coronis (Greek mythology)
k: null
Text: 'Coronis'
End Reference: Coronis (Greek mythology)
Text: ', was daughter of '
Begin Reference: Phlegyas
End Reference: Phlegyas
Text: ', King of the '
Begin Reference: Lapiths
End Reference: Lapiths
Text: '. Pregnant with '
Begin Reference: Asclepius
End Reference: Asclepius
Text: ', Coronis fell in love with '
Begin Reference: Ischys
End Reference: Ischys
Text: ', son of '
Begin Reference: Elatus
End Reference: Elatus
Text: '. A crow informed Apollo of the affair. When first informed he disbelieved the crow and turned all crows black (where they were previously white) as a punishment for spreading untruths. When he found out the truth he sent his sister, Artemis, to kill Coronis (in other stories, Apollo himself had killed Coronis). As a result he also made the crow sacred and gave them the task of announcing important deaths. Apollo rescued the baby and gave it to the '
Begin Reference: centaur
End Reference: centaur
Text: ' '
Begin Reference: Chiron
End Reference: Chiron
Text: ' to raise. Phlegyas was irate after the death of his daughter and burned the Temple of Apollo at Delphi. Apollo then killed him for what he did.'
Paragraph
