Section [1] Apollo's lyre
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Apollo Kitharoidos Antikensammlung Berlin 2.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'upright'
k: null
Text: 'Apollo with his '
Begin Reference: lyre
End Reference: lyre
Text: '. Statue from '
Begin Reference: Pergamon Museum
End Reference: Pergamon Museum
Text: ', Berlin.'
End Reference: File:Apollo Kitharoidos Antikensammlung Berlin 2.jpg
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: Hermes
End Reference: Hermes
Text: ' was born on '
Begin Reference: Mount Kyllini
k: null
Text: 'Mount Cyllene'
End Reference: Mount Kyllini
Text: ' in Arcadia. The story is told in the '
Begin Reference: Homeric Hymn
End Reference: Homeric Hymn
Text: ' to '
Begin Reference: Hermes
End Reference: Hermes
Text: '. His mother, '
Begin Reference: Maia (mythology)
k: null
Text: 'Maia'
End Reference: Maia (mythology)
Text: ', had been secretly impregnated by '
Begin Reference: Zeus
End Reference: Zeus
Text: '. Maia wrapped the infant in blankets but Hermes escaped while she was asleep.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Hermes ran to '
Begin Reference: Thessaly
End Reference: Thessaly
Text: ', where Apollo was grazing his cattle. The infant Hermes stole a number of his cows and took them to a cave in the woods near '
Begin Reference: Pylos
End Reference: Pylos
Text: ', covering their tracks. In the cave, he found a '
Begin Reference: tortoise
End Reference: tortoise
Text: ' and killed it, then removed the insides. He used one of the cow's intestines and the tortoise shell and made the first '
Begin Reference: lyre
End Reference: lyre
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Apollo complained to Maia that her son had stolen his cattle, but Hermes had already replaced himself in the blankets she had wrapped him in, so Maia refused to believe Apollo's claim. Zeus intervened and, claiming to have seen the events, sided with Apollo. Hermes then began to play music on the lyre he had invented. Apollo, a god of music, fell in love with the instrument and offered to allow exchange of the cattle for the lyre. Hence, Apollo then became a master of the lyre.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Apollo in the ''Oresteia''
Text: '
In '
Begin Reference: Aeschylus
End Reference: Aeschylus
Text: '' '
ItalicBold: 2
Begin Reference: Oresteia
End Reference: Oresteia
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' trilogy, '
Begin Reference: Clytemnestra
End Reference: Clytemnestra
Text: ' kills her husband, '
Begin Reference: King Agamemnon
End Reference: King Agamemnon
Text: ' because he had sacrificed their daughter '
Begin Reference: Iphigenia
End Reference: Iphigenia
Text: ' to proceed forward with the Trojan war, and '
Begin Reference: Cassandra
End Reference: Cassandra
Text: ', a prophetess of Apollo. Apollo gives an order through the Oracle at Delphi that Agamemnon's son, '
Begin Reference: Orestes
End Reference: Orestes
Text: ', is to kill Clytemnestra and '
Begin Reference: Aegisthus
End Reference: Aegisthus
Text: ', her lover. Orestes and Pylades carry out the revenge, and consequently Orestes is pursued by the '
Begin Reference: Erinyes
End Reference: Erinyes
Text: ' (Furies, female personifications of '
Begin Reference: revenge
k: null
Text: 'vengeance'
End Reference: revenge
Text: ').'
Paragraph
Text: 'Apollo and the Furies argue about whether the '
Begin Reference: matricide
End Reference: matricide
Text: ' was justified; Apollo holds that the bond of marriage is sacred and Orestes was avenging his father, whereas the Erinyes say that the bond of blood between mother and son is more meaningful than the bond of marriage. They invade his temple, and he says that the matter should be brought before Athena. Apollo promises to protect Orestes, as Orestes has become Apollo's supplicant. Apollo advocates Orestes at the trial, and ultimately Athena rules with Apollo.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Other stories
Text: '
Apollo killed the '
Begin Reference: Aloadae
End Reference: Aloadae
Text: ' when they attempted to storm '
Begin Reference: Mount Olympus (Mountain)
k: null
Text: 'Mt. Olympus'
End Reference: Mount Olympus (Mountain)
Text: '.'
