Section [2] Musical contests
Paragraph
Section [3] Pan
Text: '
Once '
Begin Reference: Pan (mythology)
k: null
Text: 'Pan'
End Reference: Pan (mythology)
Text: ' had the audacity to compare his music with that of Apollo, and to challenge Apollo, the god of the '
Begin Reference: kithara
End Reference: kithara
Text: ', to a trial of skill. '
Begin Reference: Tmolus
End Reference: Tmolus
Text: ', the mountain-god, was chosen to umpire. Pan blew on his pipes, and with his rustic melody gave great satisfaction to himself and his faithful follower, '
Begin Reference: Midas
End Reference: Midas
Text: ', who happened to be present. Then Apollo struck the strings of his lyre. Tmolus at once awarded the victory to Apollo, and all but Midas agreed with the judgment. He dissented, and questioned the justice of the award. Apollo would not suffer such a depraved pair of ears any longer, and caused them to become the ears of a '
Begin Reference: donkey
End Reference: donkey
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Section [3] Marsyas
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:IAM 400T - Statue of Marsyas.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'upright'
k: null
Begin Reference: Marsyas
End Reference: Marsyas
Text: ' under Apollo's punishment, '
Begin Reference: Istanbul Archaeology Museums
k: null
Text: 'İstanbul Archaeology Museum'
End Reference: Istanbul Archaeology Museums
End Reference: File:IAM 400T - Statue of Marsyas.jpg
Paragraph
Text: 'Apollo has ominous aspects aside from his plague-bringing, death-dealing arrows: '
Begin Reference: Marsyas
End Reference: Marsyas
Text: ' was a '
Begin Reference: satyr
End Reference: satyr
Text: ' who challenged Apollo to a contest of music. He had found an '
Begin Reference: aulos
End Reference: aulos
Text: ' on the ground, tossed away after being invented by '
Begin Reference: Athena
End Reference: Athena
Text: ' because it made her cheeks puffy. The contest was judged by the '
Begin Reference: Muse
End Reference: Muse
Text: 's.'
Paragraph
Text: 'After they each performed, both were deemed equal until Apollo decreed they play and sing at the same time. As Apollo played the '
Begin Reference: lyre
End Reference: lyre
Text: ', this was easy to do. Marsyas could not do this, as he only knew how to use the flute and could not sing at the same time. Apollo was declared the winner because of this. Apollo '
Begin Reference: flaying
k: null
Text: 'flayed'
End Reference: flaying
Text: ' Marsyas alive in a cave near '
Begin Reference: Celaenae
End Reference: Celaenae
Text: ' in '
Begin Reference: Phrygia
End Reference: Phrygia
Text: ' for his '
Begin Reference: hubris
End Reference: hubris
Text: ' to challenge a god. He then nailed Marsyas' shaggy skin to a nearby pine-tree. Marsyas' blood turned into the river '
Begin Reference: Marsyas (river)
k: null
Text: 'Marsyas'
End Reference: Marsyas (river)
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Another variation is that Apollo played his instrument (the lyre) upside down. Marsyas could not do this with his instrument (the '
Begin Reference: flute
End Reference: flute
Text: '), and so Apollo hung him from a tree and flayed him alive.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Man Myth and Magic'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' by Richard Cavendish'
Close Tag: ref
Paragraph
