End Reference: Hyacinthia
Text: ', '
Begin Reference: Metageitnia
End Reference: Metageitnia
Text: ', '
Begin Reference: Pyanepsia
End Reference: Pyanepsia
Text: ', '
Begin Reference: Pythia
End Reference: Pythia
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: Thargelia
End Reference: Thargelia
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Section [0] Attributes and symbols
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Ai-Khanoum-gold stater of Antiochos1.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '250px'
k: null
Text: 'Gold stater of the '
Begin Reference: Seleucid
End Reference: Seleucid
Text: ' king '
Begin Reference: Antiochus I Soter
End Reference: Antiochus I Soter
Text: ' (reigned 281–261 BCE) showing on the reverse a nude Apollo holding his key attributes: two arrows and a bow'
End Reference: File:Ai-Khanoum-gold stater of Antiochos1.jpg
Text: '
Apollo's most common attributes were the bow and '
Begin Reference: arrow
End Reference: arrow
Text: '. Other attributes of his included the '
Begin Reference: kithara
End Reference: kithara
Text: ' (an advanced version of the common '
Begin Reference: lyre
End Reference: lyre
Text: '), the '
Begin Reference: plectrum
End Reference: plectrum
Text: ' and the sword. Another common emblem was the '
Begin Reference: sacrificial tripod
End Reference: sacrificial tripod
Text: ', representing his prophetic powers. The '
Begin Reference: Pythian Games
End Reference: Pythian Games
Text: ' were held in Apollo's honor every four years at '
Begin Reference: Delphi
End Reference: Delphi
Text: '. The '
Begin Reference: bay laurel
End Reference: bay laurel
Text: ' plant was used in expiatory sacrifices and in making the '
Begin Reference: laurel wreath
k: null
Text: 'crown of victory'
End Reference: laurel wreath
Text: ' at these games.'
Paragraph
Text: 'The '
Begin Reference: palm tree
End Reference: palm tree
Text: ' was also sacred to Apollo because he had been born under one in '
Begin Reference: Delos
End Reference: Delos
Text: '. Animals sacred to Apollo included '
Begin Reference: wolf
k: null
Text: 'wolves'
End Reference: wolf
Text: ', dolphins, '
Begin Reference: roe deer
End Reference: roe deer
Text: ', '
Begin Reference: swan
End Reference: swan
Text: 's, '
Begin Reference: cicada
End Reference: cicada
Text: 's (symbolizing music and song), '
Begin Reference: hawk
End Reference: hawk
Text: 's, '
Begin Reference: raven
End Reference: raven
Text: 's, '
Begin Reference: crow
End Reference: crow
Text: 's, snakes (referencing Apollo's function as the god of prophecy), mice and '
Begin Reference: griffin
End Reference: griffin
Text: 's, mythical eagle–lion hybrids of Eastern origin.'
Paragraph
Begin Reference: File:Apolocitaredo8.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '250px'
k: null
Text: ''''
Begin Reference: Apollo Citharoedus
End Reference: Apollo Citharoedus
Text: ''' ("Apollo with a kithara"), '
Begin Reference: Musei Capitolini
End Reference: Musei Capitolini
Text: ', Rome'
End Reference: File:Apolocitaredo8.jpg
Text: '
As god of colonization, Apollo gave oracular guidance on colonies, especially during the height of colonization, 750–550 BCE. According to Greek tradition, he helped '
Begin Reference: Crete
k: null
Text: 'Cretan'
End Reference: Crete
Text: ' or '
Begin Reference: Arcadia
End Reference: Arcadia
Text: 'n colonists found the city of '
Begin Reference: Troy
End Reference: Troy
Text: '. However, this story may reflect a cultural influence which had the reverse direction: '
Begin Reference: Hittites
k: null
Text: 'Hittite'
End Reference: Hittites
Text: ' '
Begin Reference: Cuneiform script
k: null
Text: 'cuneiform'
End Reference: Cuneiform script
Text: ' texts mention a Minor Asian god called '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Appaliunas'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' or '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Apalunas'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' in connection with the city of '
Begin Reference: Wilusa
End Reference: Wilusa
Text: ' attested in Hittite inscriptions, which is now generally regarded as being identical with the Greek '
Begin Reference: Troy
k: null
Text: 'Ilion'
End Reference: Troy
Text: ' by most scholars. In this interpretation, Apollo's title of '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Lykegenes'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' can simply be read as "born in Lycia", which effectively severs the god's supposed link with wolves (possibly a '
Begin Reference: folk etymology
End Reference: folk etymology
Text: ').'
Paragraph
Text: 'In literary contexts, Apollo represents harmony, order, and reason—characteristics contrasted with those of '
Begin Reference: Dionysus
End Reference: Dionysus
Text: ', god of wine, who represents ecstasy and disorder. The contrast between the roles of these gods is reflected in the adjectives '
Begin Reference: Apollonian and Dionysian
End Reference: Apollonian and Dionysian
Text: '. However, the Greeks thought of the two qualities as complementary: the two gods are brothers, and when Apollo at winter left for '
Begin Reference: Hyperborea
End Reference: Hyperborea
Text: ', he would leave the Delphic oracle to Dionysus. This contrast appears to be shown on the two sides of the '
Begin Reference: Borghese Vase
End Reference: Borghese Vase
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Apollo is often associated with the '
Begin Reference: Golden mean (philosophy)
k: null
Text: 'Golden Mean'
End Reference: Golden mean (philosophy)
Text: '. This is the Greek '
Begin Reference: Ideal (ethics)
k: null
Text: 'ideal'
End Reference: Ideal (ethics)
Text: ' of '
Begin Reference: moderation
End Reference: moderation
Text: ' and a '
Begin Reference: virtue
End Reference: virtue
Text: ' that opposes '
Begin Reference: gluttony
End Reference: gluttony
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Section [0] Apollo in the arts
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Apollo Saurocton Louvre.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '180px'
k: null
Text: 'The Louvre ''Apollo Sauroctonos'', Roman copy after  '
Begin Reference: Praxiteles
End Reference: Praxiteles
Text: ' (360 BC)'
End Reference: File:Apollo Saurocton Louvre.jpg
Text: '
'
ItalicBold: 3
Text: 'Apollo'
ItalicBold: 3
Text: ' is a common theme in Greek and Roman art and also in the art of the '
Begin Reference: Renaissance
End Reference: Renaissance
Text: '. The earliest Greek word for a statue is "delight" ('
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'ἄγαλμα'
End Template: lang
Text: ', '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'agalma'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: '), and the sculptors tried to create forms which would inspire such guiding vision. Greek art puts into '
ItalicBold: 3
Text: 'Apollo'
ItalicBold: 3
Text: ' the highest degree of power and beauty that can be imagined. The sculptors derived this from observations on human beings, but they also embodied in concrete form, issues beyond the reach of ordinary thought.'
Paragraph
Text: 'The naked bodies of the statues are associated with the cult of the body that was essentially a religious activity. The muscular frames and limbs combined with slim waists indicate the Greek desire for health, and the physical capacity which was necessary in the hard Greek environment. The statues of Apollo embody beauty, balance and inspire awe before the beauty of the world.'
Paragraph
Text: 'The evolution of the Greek sculpture can be observed in his depictions from the almost static formal '
Begin Reference: Kouros
End Reference: Kouros
Text: ' type in '
Begin Reference: Archaic period in Greece
k: null
Text: 'early archaic period'
End Reference: Archaic period in Greece
Text: ', to the representation of motion in a relative harmonious whole in '
Begin Reference: Archaic period in Greece
k: null
Text: 'late archaic period'
End Reference: Archaic period in Greece
Text: '. In '
Begin Reference: classical Greece
End Reference: classical Greece
Text: ' the emphasis is not given to the illusive imaginative reality represented by the ideal forms, but to the analogies and the interaction of the members in the whole, a method created by '
Begin Reference: Polykleitos
End Reference: Polykleitos
Text: '. Finally '
Begin Reference: Praxiteles
End Reference: Praxiteles
Text: ' seems to be released from any art and religious conformities, and his masterpieces are a mixture of '
Begin Reference: Realism (arts)
k: null
Text: 'naturalism'
End Reference: Realism (arts)
Text: ' with stylization.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Art and Greek philosophy
Text: '
The evolution of the Greek art seems to go parallel with the Greek philosophical conceptions, which changed from the natural-philosophy of '
Begin Reference: Thales
End Reference: Thales
Text: ' to the '
Begin Reference: Metaphysics
k: null
Text: 'metaphysical'
End Reference: Metaphysics
Text: ' theory of '
Begin Reference: Pythagoras
End Reference: Pythagoras
Text: '. Thales searched for a simple material-form directly perceptible by the senses, behind the appearances of things, and his theory is also related to the older '
Begin Reference: animism
End Reference: animism
Text: '. This was paralleled in sculpture by the absolute representation of vigorous life, through unnaturally simplified forms.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Homann63']
Text: 'E. Homann-Wedeking. Transl. J.R. Foster (1968). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Art of the world. Archaic Greece'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', Methuen '
Text: '& '
Text: 'Co Ltd. London, pp 63-65, 193.'
Close Tag: ref
Paragraph
Text: 'Pythagoras believed that behind the appearance of things, there was the permanent principle of mathematics, and that the forms were based on a transcendental mathematical relation.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'C.M. Bowra (1957). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'The Greek experience'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', p.166.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The forms on earth, are imperfect imitations ('
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'εἰκόνες'
End Template: lang
Text: ', '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'eikones'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', "images") of the celestial world of numbers. His ideas had a great influence on post-Archaic art, and the Greek architects and sculptors were always trying to find the mathematical relation, that would lead to the esthetic perfection.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Carpenter55']
Text: 'R. Carpenter (1975). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'The esthetic basis of Greek art'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: '. Indiana University Press. p. 55-58.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' ('
Begin Reference: Aesthetic canon
k: null
Text: 'canon'
End Reference: Aesthetic canon
Text: ').'
Paragraph
Text: 'In classical Greece, '
Begin Reference: Anaxagoras
End Reference: Anaxagoras
Text: ' asserted that a divine reason (mind) gave order to the seeds of the universe, and '
Begin Reference: Plato
End Reference: Plato
Text: ' extended the Greek belief of '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'ideal forms'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' to his metaphysical theory of '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'forms'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' ('
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'ideai'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', "ideas"). The forms on earth are imperfect duplicates of the intellectual celestial ideas. The Greek words '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'oida'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' ('
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'οἶδα'
End Template: lang
Text: ', "(I) know") and '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'eidos'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' ('
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'εἶδος'
End Template: lang
Text: ', "species") have the same root as the word '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'idea'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' ('
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'ἰδέα'
End Template: lang
Text: '),'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Carpenter55']
Text: ' indicating how the Greek mind moved from the gift of the senses, to the principles beyond the senses. The artists in Plato's time moved away from his theories and art tends to be a mixture of naturalism with stylization. The Greek sculptors considered the senses more important, and the proportions were used to unite the sensible with the intellectual.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Archaic sculpture
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:KAMA Kouros Porte Sacrée.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
