Paragraph
Begin Reference: Kouros
End Reference: Kouros
Text: ' ('
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'male youth'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ') is the modern term given to those representations of standing male youths which first appear in the '
Begin Reference: archaic period in Greece
End Reference: archaic period in Greece
Text: '. This type served certain religious needs and was first proposed for what was previously thought to be depictions of '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Apollo'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'V.I. Leonardos(1895). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Archaelogiki Ephimeris'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', Col 75, n 1.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Lechat (1904). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'La sculpture Attic avant Phidias'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', p. 23.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The first statues are certainly still and formal. The formality of their stance seems to be related with the '
Begin Reference: Egypt
End Reference: Egypt
Text: 'ian precedent, but it was accepted for a good reason. The sculptors had a clear idea of what a young man is, and embodied the archaic smile of good manners, the firm and springy step, the balance of the body, dignity, and youthful happiness. When they tried to depict the most abiding qualities of men, it was because men had common roots with the unchanging gods.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Bowra144']
Text: 'C.M. Bowra (1957). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'The Greek experience'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', pp. 144-152.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The adoption of a standard recognizable type for a long time, is probably because nature gives preference in survival of a type which has long be adopted by the climatic conditions, and also due to the general Greek belief that nature expresses itself in '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'ideal forms'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' that can be imagined and represented.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Carpenter55']
Text: ' These forms expressed immortality. Apollo was the immortal god of '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'ideal balance and order'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: '. His shrine in '
Begin Reference: Delphi
End Reference: Delphi
Text: ', that he shared in winter with Dionysius had the inscriptions: '
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'γνῶθι σεαυτόν'
End Template: lang
Text: ' (gnōthi seautón = "know thyself") and '
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'μηδὲν ἄγαν'
End Template: lang
Text: ' ('
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'mēdén ágan'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', "nothing in excess"), and '
Begin Template: lang
k: null
Text: 'grc'
k: null
Text: 'ἐγγύα πάρα δ'ἄτη'
End Template: lang
Text: ' (eggýa pára d'atē, "make a pledge and mischief is nigh").'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'See '
Begin Template: LSJ
