k: null
Text: 'New York Kouros, Met. Mus. 32.11.1, marble (620–610 BC), '
Begin Reference: Metropolitan Museum of Art
End Reference: Metropolitan Museum of Art
End Reference: File:WLA metmuseum Marble statue of a kouros youth 2.jpg
Text: '
In the first large-scale depictions during the early archaic period (640–580 BC), the artists tried to draw one's attention to look into the interior of the face and the body which were not represented as lifeless masses, but as being full of life. The Greeks maintained, until late in their civilization, an almost '
Begin Reference: animism
k: null
Text: 'animistic'
End Reference: animism
Text: ' idea that the statues are in some sense alive. This embodies the belief that the image was somehow the god or man himself.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'C.M. Bowra. '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'The Greek experience'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', p.159.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' A fine example is the statue of the '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Sacred gate Kouros'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' which was found at the cemetery of '
Begin Reference: Dipylon
End Reference: Dipylon
Text: ' in Athens ('
Begin Reference: Dipylon
End Reference: Dipylon
Text: ' '
Begin Reference: Kouros
End Reference: Kouros
Text: '). The statue is the "thing in itself", and his slender face with the deep eyes express an intellectual eternity. According to the Greek tradition the '
Begin Reference: Dipylon
k: null
Text: 'Dipylon master'
End Reference: Dipylon
Text: ' was named '
Begin Reference: Daedalus
End Reference: Daedalus
Text: ', and in his statues the limbs were freed from the body, giving the impression that the statues could move. It is considered that he created also the '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'New York kouros'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', which is the oldest fully preserved statue of '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Kouros'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' type, and seems to be the incarnation of the god himself.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Homann63']
Paragraph
Begin Reference: File:7262 - Piraeus Arch. Museum, Athens - The Piraeus Apollo - Photo by Giovanni Dall'Orto, Nov 14 2009.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'left'
k: null
Text: '180px'
k: null
Begin Reference: Piraeus Apollo
End Reference: Piraeus Apollo
Text: ', archaic-style bronze, '
Begin Reference: Archaeological Museum of Piraeus
End Reference: Archaeological Museum of Piraeus
End Reference: File:7262 - Piraeus Arch. Museum, Athens - The Piraeus Apollo - Photo by Giovanni Dall'Orto, Nov 14 2009.jpg
Text: '
The animistic idea as the representation of the imaginative reality, is sanctified in the '
Begin Reference: Homeric
End Reference: Homeric
Text: ' poems and in Greek myths, in stories of the god '
Begin Reference: Hephaestus
End Reference: Hephaestus
Text: ' ('
Begin Reference: Phaistos
End Reference: Phaistos
Text: ') and the mythic '
Begin Reference: Daedalus
End Reference: Daedalus
Text: ' (the builder of the '
Begin Reference: labyrinth
End Reference: labyrinth
Text: ') that made images which moved of their own accord. This kind of art goes back to the '
Begin Reference: Minoan civilization
k: null
Text: 'Minoan'
End Reference: Minoan civilization
Text: ' period, when its main theme was the representation of motion in a specific moment.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Schachermeyer242']
Text: 'F. Schachermeyer (1964). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Die Minoische Kultur des alten Creta'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', Kohlhammer Stuttgart, pp. 242-244.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' These free-standing statues were usually marble, but also the form rendered in limestone, bronze, ivory and terracotta.'
Paragraph
Text: 'The earliest examples of life-sized statues of Apollo, may be two figures from the '
Begin Reference: Ionians
k: null
Text: 'Ionic'
End Reference: Ionians
Text: ' sanctuary on the island of '
Begin Reference: Delos
End Reference: Delos
Text: '. Such statues were found across the Greek speaking world, the preponderance of these were found at the sanctuaries of Apollo with more than one hundred from the sanctuary of '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Apollo Ptoios'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', '
Begin Reference: Boeotia
End Reference: Boeotia
Text: ' alone.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'J. Ducat (1971). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Les Kouroi des Ptoion'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: '.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The last stage in the development of the '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Kouros type'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' is the late archaic period (520–485 BC), in which the Greek sculpture attained a full knowledge of human anatomy and used to create a relative harmonious whole. Ranking from the very few bronzes survived to us is the masterpiece bronze '
Begin Reference: Piraeus Apollo
End Reference: Piraeus Apollo
Text: '. It was found in '
Begin Reference: Piraeus
End Reference: Piraeus
Text: ', the harbour of Athens. The statue originally held the bow in its left hand, and a cup of pouring libation in its right hand. It probably comes from north-eastern '
Begin Reference: Peloponnesus
End Reference: Peloponnesus
Text: '. The emphasis is given in anatomy, and it is one of the first attempts to represent a kind of motion, and beauty relative to proportions, which appear mostly in post-Archaic art. The statue throws some light on an artistic centre which, with an independently developed harder, simpler, and heavier style, restricts '
Begin Reference: Ionia
End Reference: Ionia
Text: 'n influence in Athens. Finally, this is the germ from which the art of '
Begin Reference: Polykleitos
End Reference: Polykleitos
Text: ' was to grow two or three generations later.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Homann144']
Text: 'Homann-Wedeking (1966). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Art of the World. Archaic Greece'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' pp. 144-150.'
Close Tag: ref
Paragraph
Section [1] Classical Sculpture
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Apollon de Mantoue Louvre MA689.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'left'
k: null
Text: '180px'
k: null
Text: 'Apollo of the "Mantoua type", marble Roman copy after a 5th-century-BC Greek original attributed to '
Begin Reference: Polykleitos
End Reference: Polykleitos
Text: ', Musée du Louvre'
End Reference: File:Apollon de Mantoue Louvre MA689.jpg
Text: '
In the next century which is the beginning of the '
Begin Reference: Classical Greece
k: null
Text: 'Classical period'
End Reference: Classical Greece
Text: ', it was considered that beauty in visible things as in everything else, consisted of symmetry and proportions. The artists tried also to represent motion in a specific moment ('
Begin Reference: Myron
End Reference: Myron
Text: '), which may be considered as the reappearance of the dormant '
Begin Reference: Minoan civilization
k: null
Text: 'Minoan'
End Reference: Minoan civilization
Text: ' element.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Schachermeyer242']
Text: ' Anatomy and geometry are fused in one, and each does something to the other. The Greek sculptors tried to clarify it by looking for mathematical proportions, just as they sought some reality behind appearances. '
Begin Reference: Polykleitos
End Reference: Polykleitos
Text: ' in his '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Canon'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' wrote that beauty consists in the proportion not of the elements (materials), but of the parts, that is the interrelation of parts with one another and with the whole. It seems that he was influenced by the theories of '
Begin Reference: Pythagoras
End Reference: Pythagoras
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: '"Each part (finger, palm, arm, etc) transmitted its individual existence to the next, and then to the whole" : '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Canon of '
Begin Reference: Polykleitos
End Reference: Polykleitos
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', also '
Begin Reference: Plotinus
End Reference: Plotinus
Text: ', '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Ennead'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' I vi. i: Nigel Spivey (1997). '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Greek art'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', Phaidon Press Ltd. London. pp. 290-294.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '
The famous '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Apollo of Mantua'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' and its variants are early forms of the '
Begin Reference: Apollo Citharoedus
End Reference: Apollo Citharoedus
Text: ' statue type, in which the god holds the '
Begin Reference: cithara
End Reference: cithara
Text: ' in his left arm. The type is represented by '
Begin Reference: neo-Attic
End Reference: neo-Attic
Text: ' Imperial Roman copies of the late 1st or early 2nd century, modelled upon a supposed Greek bronze original made in the second quarter of the 5th century BCE, in a style similar to works of '
Begin Reference: Polykleitos
End Reference: Polykleitos
Text: ' but more archaic. The Apollo held the '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'cythara'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' against his extended left arm, of which in the Louvre example, a fragment of one twisting scrolling horn upright remains against his biceps.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Though the proportions were always important in Greek art, the appeal of the Greek sculptures eludes any explanation by proportion alone. The statues of Apollo were thought to incarnate his living presence, and these representations of illusive imaginative reality had deep roots in the '
Begin Reference: Minoan civilization
k: null
Text: 'Minoan'
End Reference: Minoan civilization
Text: ' period, and in the beliefs of the first '
Begin Reference: Greek language
k: null
Text: 'Greek'
End Reference: Greek language
Text: ' speaking people who entered the region during the bronze-age. Just as the Greeks saw the mountains, forests, sea and rivers as inhabited by concrete beings, so nature in all of its manifestations possesses clear form, and the form of a work of art. Spiritual life is incorporated in matter, when it is given artistic form. Just as in the arts the Greeks sought some reality behind appearances, so in mathematics they sought permanent principles which could be applied wherever the conditions were the same. Artists and sculptors tried to find this ideal order in relation with mathematics, but they believed that this ideal order revealed itself not so much to the dispassionate intellect, as to the whole sentient self.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Homann63']
Text: ' Things as we see them, and as they really are, are one, that each stresses the nature of the other in a single unity.'
Paragraph
Section [1] Pediments and Friezes
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Apollo west pediment Olympia copy MFA Munich.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'upright'
k: null
Text: 'Apollo, West Pediment Olympia. Munich, copy from original, 460 BC at the '
Begin Reference: Temple of Zeus
End Reference: Temple of Zeus
Text: ', '
Begin Reference: Olympia, Greece
End Reference: Olympia, Greece
Text: '.'
End Reference: File:Apollo west pediment Olympia copy MFA Munich.jpg
Text: '
In the archaic pediments and friezes of the temples, the artists had a problem to fit a group of figures into an isosceles triangle with acute angles at the base.'
Paragraph
Text: 'The '
Begin Reference: Siphnian Treasury
End Reference: Siphnian Treasury
Text: ' in '
Begin Reference: Delphi
End Reference: Delphi
Text: ' was one of the first Greek buildings utilizing the solution to put the dominating form in the middle, and to complete the descending scale of height with other figures sitting or kneeling. The pediment shows the story of '
Begin Reference: Heracles
End Reference: Heracles
Text: ' stealing Apollo's tripod that was strongly associated with his oracular inspiration. Their two figures hold the centre. In the pediment of the temple of '
Begin Reference: Zeus
End Reference: Zeus
Text: ' in '
Begin Reference: Olympia, Greece
k: null
Text: 'Olympia'
End Reference: Olympia, Greece
Text: ', the single figure of Apollo is dominating the scene.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Bowra144']
Paragraph
Begin Reference: File:Part of the Bassae Frieze at the British Museum.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'left'
k: null
Text: 'Part of the '
Begin Reference: Bassae Frieze
End Reference: Bassae Frieze
Text: ' at the '
Begin Reference: British Museum
End Reference: British Museum
Text: '. Apollo and Artemis in the northeast corner.'
End Reference: File:Part of the Bassae Frieze at the British Museum.jpg
Text: '
These representations rely on presenting scenes directly to the eye for their own visible sake. They care for the schematic arrangements of bodies in space, but only as parts in a larger whole. While each scene has its own character and completeness it must fit into the general sequence to which it belongs. In these archaic pediments the sculptors use empty intervals, to suggest a passage to and fro a busy battlefield. The artists seem to have been dominated by geometrical pattern and order, and this was improved when classical art brought a greater freedom and economy.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Bowra144']
Paragraph
Section [1] Hellenistic Greece-Rome
Text: '
Apollo as a handsome beardless young man, is often depicted with a '
Begin Reference: kithara
End Reference: kithara
Text: ' (as '
Begin Reference: Apollo Citharoedus
End Reference: Apollo Citharoedus
Text: ') or bow in his hand, or reclining on a tree (the '
Begin Reference: Apollo Lykeios
End Reference: Apollo Lykeios
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: Apollo Sauroctonos
End Reference: Apollo Sauroctonos
Text: ' types). The '
Begin Reference: Apollo Belvedere
End Reference: Apollo Belvedere
Text: ' is a '
Begin Reference: marble
End Reference: marble
Text: ' sculpture that was rediscovered in the late 15th century; for centuries it epitomized the ideals of '
Begin Reference: Classical Antiquity
End Reference: Classical Antiquity
Text: ' for Europeans, from the '
Begin Reference: Renaissance
End Reference: Renaissance
Text: ' through the 19th century. The marble is a '
Begin Reference: Hellenistic Greece
k: null
Text: 'Hellenistic'
End Reference: Hellenistic Greece
Text: ' or Roman copy of a bronze original by the Greek sculptor '
Begin Reference: Leochares
End Reference: Leochares
Text: ', made between 350 and 325 BCE.'
Paragraph
Text: 'The life-size so-called "'
Begin Reference: Adonis
End Reference: Adonis
Text: '" found in 1780 on the site of a '
ItalicBold: 2
Begin Reference: Roman villa
k: null
Text: 'villa suburbana'
End Reference: Roman villa
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' near the '
Begin Reference: Via Labicana
End Reference: Via Labicana
Text: ' in the Roman suburb of Centocelle is identified as an Apollo by modern scholars. In the late 2nd century CE floor mosaic from '
Begin Reference: El Djem
End Reference: El Djem
Text: ', Roman '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'Thysdrus'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', he is identifiable as '
Begin Reference: Helios
k: null
Text: 'Apollo Helios'
End Reference: Helios
Text: ' by his effulgent '
Begin Reference: Halo (religious iconography)
k: null
Text: 'halo'
End Reference: Halo (religious iconography)
Text: ', though now even a god's divine '
Begin Reference: nudity
k: null
Text: 'nakedness'
End Reference: nudity
Text: ' is concealed by his cloak, a mark of increasing conventions of modesty in the later '
Begin Reference: Roman Empire
k: null
Text: 'Empire'
End Reference: Roman Empire
Text: '.'
Paragraph
Text: 'Another haloed Apollo in mosaic, from '
Begin Reference: Hadrumentum
End Reference: Hadrumentum
Text: ', is in the museum at '
Begin Reference: Sousse
End Reference: Sousse
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Begin Template: cite web
k: url
Text: 'http://web.archive.org/web/20080708143541/http://www.tunisiaonline.com/mosaics/mosaic05b.html '
k: title
Text: 'Mosaics in Tunisia,Apollo and the Muses '
k: publisher
Text: 'Web.archive.org '
k: date
Text: '8 July 2008 '
k: accessdate
Text: '30 July 2013'
End Template: cite web
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The conventions of this representation, head tilted, lips slightly parted, large-eyed, curling '
Begin Reference: Hairstyle
k: null
Text: 'hair cut'
End Reference: Hairstyle
Text: ' in locks grazing the neck, were developed in the 3rd century BCE to depict '
Begin Reference: Alexander the Great
End Reference: Alexander the Great
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Bieber 1964, Yalouris 1980.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Some time after this mosaic was executed, the earliest depictions of Christ would also be beardless and haloed.'
Paragraph
Section [0] Modern reception
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Onthemorningthomas4.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '''The Overthrow of Apollo and the Pagan Gods'', watercolour from '
Begin Reference: William Blake's illustrations of On the Morning of Christ's Nativity
k: null
Text: 'William Blake's illustrations of ''On the Morning of Christ's Nativity'''
End Reference: William Blake's illustrations of On the Morning of Christ's Nativity
Text: ' (1809)'
End Reference: File:Onthemorningthomas4.jpg
Paragraph
Text: 'Apollo has often featured in postclassical art and literature. '
Begin Reference: Percy Bysshe Shelley
End Reference: Percy Bysshe Shelley
Text: ' composed a "Hymn of Apollo" (1820), and the god's instruction of the Muses formed the subject of '
Begin Reference: Igor Stravinsky
End Reference: Igor Stravinsky
Text: ''s '
ItalicBold: 2
Begin Reference: Apollon musagète
End Reference: Apollon musagète
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' (1927–1928).'
Paragraph
Text: 'In discussion of the arts, a distinction is sometimes made between the '
Begin Reference: Apollonian and Dionysian
End Reference: Apollonian and Dionysian
Text: ' impulses where the former is concerned with imposing intellectual order and the latter with chaotic creativity. '
Begin Reference: Friedrich Nietzsche
End Reference: Friedrich Nietzsche
Text: ' argued that a fusion of the two was most desirable. '
Begin Reference: Carl Jung
End Reference: Carl Jung
Text: ''s '
Begin Reference: Apollo archetype
End Reference: Apollo archetype
Text: ' represents what he saw as the disposition in people to over-intellectualise and maintain emotional distance.'
